Example \(\PageIndex{2}\) Simplify \(\dfrac{\sec \left(	heta ight)}{	an \left(	heta ight)}\). Solution We can simplify this by rewriting both functions in terms of sine and cosine \[\dfrac{	ext{sec}(	heta)}{	ext{tan}(	heta)} = \dfrac{1/	ext{cos}(	heta)}{	ext{sin}(	heta)/	ext{cos}(	heta)}
onumber\] To divide the fractions we could invert and multiply \[=\dfrac{1}{\cos \left(	heta ight)} \dfrac{\cos \left(	heta ight)}{\sin \left(	heta ight)}
onumber\] cancelling the cosines, \[=\dfrac{1}{\sin \left(	heta ight)} =\csc \left(	heta ight)
onumber\] simplifying and using the identity

Example \(\PageIndex{3}\) Prove the identity \(\dfrac{1+\cot (\alpha )}{\csc (\alpha )} =\sin (\alpha )+\cos (\alpha )\). Solution Since the left side seems a bit more complicated, we will start there and simplify the expression until we obtain the right side. We can use the right side as a guide for what might be good steps to make. In this case, the left side involves a fraction while the right side doesn’t, which suggests we should look to see if the fraction can be reduced. Additionally, since the right side involves sine and cosine and the left does not, it suggests that rewriting the cotangent and cosecant using sine and cosine might be a good idea. \[\dfrac{1+\cot (\alpha )}{\csc (\alpha )}
onumber\] Rewriting the cotangent and cosecant \[=\dfrac{1+\dfrac{\cos (\alpha )}{\sin (\alpha )} }{\dfrac{1}{\sin (\alpha )} }
onumber\] To divide the fractions, we invert and multiply \[=\left(1+\dfrac{\cos (\alpha )}{\sin (\alpha )} ight)\dfrac{\sin (\alpha )}{1}
onumber\] Distributing, \[=1\cdot \dfrac{\sin (\alpha )}{1} +\dfrac{\cos (\alpha )}{\sin (\alpha )} \cdot \dfrac{\sin (\alpha )}{1}
onumber\] Simplifying the fractions, \[=\sin (\alpha )+\cos (\alpha )
onumber\] Establishing the identity. Notice that in the second step, we could have combined the 1 and \(\dfrac{\cos (\alpha )}{\sin (\alpha )}\) before inverting and multiplying. It is very common when proving or simplifying identities for there to be more than one way to obtain the same result. We can also utilize identities we have previously learned, like the Pythagorean Identity, while simplifying or proving identities.

Example \(\PageIndex{4}\) Establish the identity \(\dfrac{\cos ^{2} \left(	heta ight)}{1+\sin \left(	heta ight)} =1-\sin \left(	heta ight)\). Solution Since the left side of the identity is more complicated, it makes sense to start there. To simplify this, we will have to reduce the fraction, which would require the numerator to have a factor in common with the denominator. Additionally, we notice that the right side only involves sine. Both of these suggest that we need to convert the cosine into something involving sine. Recall the Pythagorean Identity told us \(\cos ^{2} (	heta )+\sin ^{2} (	heta )=1\). By moving one of the trig functions to the other side, we can establish: \[\sin ^{2} (	heta )=1-\cos ^{2} (	heta )\quad 	ext{ and }\quad \cos ^{2} (	heta )=1-\sin ^{2} (	heta )
onumber\] Utilizing this, we now can establish the identity. We start on one side and manipulate: \[\dfrac{\cos ^{2} \left(	heta ight)}{1+\sin \left(	heta ight)}
onumber\] Utilizing the Pythagorean Identity \[=\dfrac{1-\sin ^{2} \left(	heta ight)}{1+\sin \left(	heta ight)}
onumber\] Factoring the numerator \[=\dfrac{\left(1-\sin \left(	heta ight)ight)\left(1+\sin \left(	heta ight)ight)}{1+\sin \left(	heta ight)}
onumber\] Cancelling the like factors \[=1-\sin \left(	heta ight)
onumber\] Establishing the identity

Example \(\PageIndex{5}\) If \(	an (	heta )=\dfrac{2}{7}\) and \(	heta\) is in the 3\({}^{rd}\) quadrant, find \(\cos (	heta )\). Solution There are two approaches to this problem, both of which work equally well. Approach 1 Since \(	an (	heta )=\dfrac{y}{x}\) and the angle is in the third quadrant, we can imagine a triangle in a circle of some radius so that the point on the circle is (-7, -2), so \(\dfrac{y}{x} =\dfrac{-2}{-7} =\dfrac{2}{7}\). Using the Pythagorean Theorem, we can find the radius of the circle: \[(-7)^{2} +(-2)^{2} =r^{2}\quad	ext{ ,so }\quad r=\sqrt{53}
onumber\] Now we can find the cosine value: \[\cos (	heta )=\dfrac{x}{r} =\dfrac{-7}{\sqrt{53} }
onumber\] Approach 2 Using the \(1+	an ^{2} (	heta )=\sec ^{2} (	heta )\) form of the Pythagorean Identity with the known tangent value, \[1+	an ^{2} (	heta )=\sec ^{2} (	heta )
onumber\] \[1+\left(\dfrac{2}{7} ight)^{2} =\sec ^{2} (	heta )
onumber\] \[\dfrac{53}{49} =\sec ^{2} (	heta )
onumber\] \[\sec (	heta )=\pm \sqrt{\dfrac{53}{49} } =\pm \dfrac{\sqrt{53} }{7}
onumber\] Since the angle is in the third quadrant, the cosine value will be negative so the secant value will also be negative. Keeping the negative result, and using definition of secant, \[\sec (	heta )=-\dfrac{\sqrt{53} }{7}
onumber\] \[\dfrac{1}{\cos (	heta )} =-\dfrac{\sqrt{53} }{7}
onumber\] Inverting both sides \[\cos (	heta )=-\dfrac{7}{\sqrt{53} } =-\dfrac{7\sqrt{53} }{53}
onumber\]
